ppsala, Sweden","Granhammar, Västra Ryd, Uppsala, Sweden":"Granhammar, Västra Ryd, Uppsala, Sweden","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Erik","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from the personal name <i>Erich</i>, ancient Germanic personal name composed of <i>ēra</i> ‘honor’ + <i>rīhhi</i> ‘powerful, rich’ (see also   Erickson  ).","Scandinavian: from a variant of the personal name <i>Erik</i> (Old Norse <i>Eiríkr</i>). See   Erickson  .","Croatian and Serbian (<b>Erić</b>): patronymic from the nickname <i>Ero</i>, denoting someone from Herzegovina (see   Herceg  ). Compare   Erich   and   Erick  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Erickson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Nels, Thor, Nils, Lars, Sven, Lief, Anders, Lennart, Iver, Elof, Erland.","Americanized form (and a rare Swedish variant) of Swedish   Ericsson   and   Eriksson  , Norwegian, Danish, and North German   Eriksen   and   Erichsen  , or of any other Scandinavian or North German patronymic from a personal name derived from Old Norse <i>Eiríkr</i>, which is composed of <i>ei</i> ‘ever, always’ (or a shortened form of <i>ein</i> ‘one, only’) + <i>rík</i> ‘power’. Compare   Ericksen  ,   Ericson  , and   Erikson  .","English (Lancashire): patronymic from the Middle English male personal name <i>Eric</i> (with the same etymology as 1 above) + <i>son</i>."]},{"name":"Erkkila","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Finnish Reino, Armas, Eino, Kristiina.  Scandinavian Mauritz.","Finnish (<b>Erkkilä</b>): habitational name from a farm so named, from the personal name <i>Erkki</i>, a Finnish form of   Eric   (see   Erickson  ), + the locative suffix <i>-la</i>."]}]},{"name":"Gregersson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Juel, Lars, Viggo.","Americanized form of Danish, Norwegian, and North German   Gr